{
  "answer": "Both poems are in the corpus.\n\n**The Ruin** appears as chapter 16 of 'Old English Elegies' (unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e). The most charged line is: \"until mighty Wyrd overturned it all\" (paragraph p-ba51da). This is the poem's climactic agent-assignment — the only force named in the entire poem is Wyrd (fate), not any conqueror, emperor, or city. The fallen place has no name; even its destroyers are unnamed. The speaker stands outside history as a pure witness.\n\n**Saqaliya** appears as chapter 21 of 'Bang-E-Dara Part 2' (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c). The most charged line is the opening couplet: \"Weep now, unburden your heart, O eye that rains down tears of blood, / For there, in sight, lies the grave of Hejazi civilization.\" (paragraph p-08760e). By the time Iqbal reaches the explicit apostrophe \"Ah, O Sicily! You are the honor of the sea\" (p-379aeb), Sicily is already loaded: it has been named as the burial ground of the Hejaz — of Islam's originary civilization.\n\n**What naming/refusing-to-name commits each speaker to:**\n\nThe Old English poet's refusal to name commits the speaker to a position of aesthetic detachment and universal impermanence. The ruined city is described only as 'the work of giants' — alien, pre-Christian, inscrutable. Wyrd, not any identifiable enemy or people, is the agent of destruction. This anonymity forecloses political mourning: the grief is elegiac and formal, not partisan. The speaker does not own this history or claim inheritance from it. The refusal to name turns the poem into a meditation on mutability itself — any city, every city.\n\nIqbal's naming commits him to political inheritance and obligation. Naming Sicily inserts it into a chain of Islamic losses — Baghdad (mourned by Hafez of Shiraz), Jahanabad (mourned by Dagh), Granada (mourned by Ibn Badrun), now Sicily (mourned by Iqbal). Each mourner is also named. To name the place is to claim it, to indict the present, and to mobilize grief: \"I shall carry you as a gift to Hindustan; I weep here myself, to make others weep there\" (p-665fb2). The naming creates an inheritance that makes mourning into a political act — grief as propaganda, grief as continuity. The anonymous Old English speaker can only witness; Iqbal's named Sicily demands a response.",
